<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-189-003 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 846 212</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Micro  April 1991 v11 n2 p24(19).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Three-dimensional optical architecture and data-parallelalgorithms for massively parallel computing.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Louri, Ahmed.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The University of Arizona Department of Electrical and ComputingEngineering develops a single-instruction, multiple-data (SIMD)three-dimensional optical computing architecture based on symbolicsubstitution logic (SSL).andP;  The demand for computer performance isever-increasing, but electronic technology suffers several majordrawbacks to achieving effective massive parallelism, includinglimited communication bandwidth and lack of cost-effectiveparallel input/output.andP;  Advantages of optical technology incontrast include massive fine-grain parallelism, speed, and highm communication, routing and architectural flexibility.andP;  SSL is anoptical computing technique that operates by transforming opticalpatterns (pixel values and spatial locations) representing datainto other patterns by predefined transformation rules.andP;  Thecurrent state of the architecture is slower than comparableelectronic array processors but can potentially deliver at least100 times the processing throughput.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Optical ComputersMassive ParallelismSystem DesignParallel AlgorithmsSystem DevelopmentFuture TechnologiesResearch and DevelopmentArizona, University of. Department of Electrical and ComputingEngineering.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Diagram of a 3D optical architecture for massively parallelcomputing. (chart)The concept of optical symbolic substitution logic. (chart)Logical structure of the optical processor array. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>